Data visualization

Scatter Plot

Plot Sepal width against sepal length:

  • Simple plot to investigate the relationship between Petal length and Sepal length in all three species
plot(iris$Petal.Length ~ iris$Sepal.Length) # if you don't know what the function does: ?plot

Assign every species a different color and add a legend:

  • Same plot as before, but now we add information about each species
plot(Petal.Length ~ Sepal.Length, data = iris, col = iris$Species, pch = 19) # col means color
legend(x = 4.5, y = 7, legend = levels(iris$Species), col = c(1:3), pch = 19)

Save your plot as pdf:

pdf("iris1.pdf") # open the pdf
plot(Petal.Length ~ Sepal.Length, data = iris, col = iris$Species, pch = 19)
legend(x = 4.5, y = 7, legend = levels(iris$Species), col = c(1:3), pch = 19)
dev.off() # close the pdf

Choose a different color:

  • you have so many different colors in R to generate beautiful plots
  • check online, e.g. http://www.stat.columbia.edu/~tzheng/files/Rcolor.pdf
library(RColorBrewer)
#display.brewer.all(n=3)
plot(Petal.Length ~ Sepal.Length, data = iris, col=brewer.pal(3, "Set2")[iris$Species], pch = 19)
legend(x=4.5, y=7, legend=levels(iris$Species), col=brewer.pal(3, "Set2"), pch=19)

ggplot2

  • ggplot2 is a very convenient tool to create graphics
  • you start with ggplot()
  • supply a dataset (iris) and aesthetic mapping (with aes())
  • add layers (like a boxplot + a scatter plot + the statistical analysis…)
library(ggplot2)
library(ggsignif)
scatter <- ggplot(data=iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length)) 
scatter + geom_point(aes(color=Species, shape=Species)) +
  xlab("Sepal Length") +  ylab("Sepal Width") +
  ggtitle("Sepal Length-Width")

Include a third feature:

scatter + geom_point(aes(color = Petal.Width, shape = Species), size = 2, alpha = I(1/2)) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(Sepal.Length)), color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = mean(Sepal.Width)), color = "red", linetype = "dashed") +
  scale_color_gradient(low = "yellow", high = "red") +
  xlab("Sepal Length") +  ylab("Sepal Width") +
  ggtitle("Sepal Length-Width")





–> The horizontal and vertical lines mark the mean of sepal.width and sepal.length, respectively

–> Different color for the different levels of petal.width

–> Different shape for every species

Boxplot

box <- ggplot(data=iris, aes(x=Species, y=Sepal.Length))
box + geom_boxplot(aes(fill=Species)) + 
  ylab("Sepal Length") + ggtitle("Iris Boxplot") +
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, geom="point", shape=5, size=4)

Statistical Analysis

Data distribution

  • before doing any statistical analysis, you need to know the distribution of the data
ggplot(iris, aes(x=Sepal.Width)) +
  geom_density(aes(group=Species, color=Species, fill=Species), alpha=0.3)

t test

  • for two species
setosa <- iris[iris$Species == "setosa", ]
versicolor <- iris[iris$Species == "versicolor", ]
t.test(x = setosa$Petal.Length, y = versicolor$Petal.Length)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  setosa$Petal.Length and versicolor$Petal.Length
## t = -39.493, df = 62.14, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -2.939618 -2.656382
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##     1.462     4.260
TwoSpecies <- rbind(setosa, versicolor)
ggplot(data=TwoSpecies, aes(x=Species, y=Sepal.Length))+ 
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=Species)) + 
  ylab("Sepal Length") + ggtitle("Iris Boxplot") +
  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, geom="point", shape=5, size=4) + 
  geom_signif(comparisons = list(c("setosa", "versicolor")), test=t.test)



- geom-signif is a very convenient function to annotate your boxplot with the statistical analysis

Pairwise t-test

pairwise.t.test(iris$Sepal.Width, iris$Species, 
                p.adj="bonferroni", paired=FALSE)

Unsupervised learning

Clustering

Hierarchical clustering

d <- dist(iris[, 1:4])
hcl <- hclust(d)
hcl
## 
## Call:
## hclust(d = d)
## 
## Cluster method   : complete 
## Distance         : euclidean 
## Number of objects: 150
plot(hcl)

Heatmap

X = as.matrix(iris[,-5])
heatmap(t(X), hclustfun = hclust, main = "Heatmap Iris")

Dimensionality reduction

Visualize all 3 species and all 4 features:

pairs(iris[, -5], col = iris[, 5], pch = 19)

Principal component analysis

library(ggfortify)
irispca <- prcomp(iris[, -5])
summary(irispca)
## Importance of components:
##                           PC1     PC2    PC3     PC4
## Standard deviation     2.0563 0.49262 0.2797 0.15439
## Proportion of Variance 0.9246 0.05307 0.0171 0.00521
## Cumulative Proportion  0.9246 0.97769 0.9948 1.00000
biplot(irispca)

autoplot(irispca, data = iris, colour = 'Species')
